description: Guide for package authors, maintainers, reviewers and editors in rOpenSci software peer-review system. This book is a guide for authors, maintainers, reviewers and editors of rOpenSci. The first section of the book contains our guidelines for creating and testing R packages. The second section is dedicated to rOpenSci’s software peer review process: what it is, our policies, and specific guides for authors, editors and reviewers throughout the process. The third and last section features our best practice for nurturing your package once it has been onboarded: how to collaborate with other developers, how to document releases, how to promote your package and how to leverage GitHub as a development platform. The third section also features a chapter for anyone wishing to start contributing to rOpenSci packages.
title: rOpenSci Packages: Development, Maintenance, and Peer Review

Use this form to suggest a new record for ROR or to request a change to an existing record. If you have more than one request, please submit a separate form for each organization/record. If you have a large number of requests, please contact registry@ror.org.

Proposed changes will be reviewed to ensure they are appropriate for ROR's scope and consistent with other records. Read about our scope and criteria for inclusion here: https://github.com/ror-community/ror-updates#ror-scope. 

ROR uses a community-based curation workflow for reviewing requests. You can read about the workflow here: https://github.com/ror-community/ror-updates#readme.

As of August 2022, the registry is updated on a rolling basis and new releases are published approximately once a month. You can follow the progress of pending updates on Github: https://github.com/ror-community/ror-updates/issues. Release notes are also posted on Github: https://github.com/ror-community/ror-updates/releases.
